<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="041" project="code-quality-and-assurance-r1">
  <metadata>
    <title>Update CI/CD and Code Quality Procedure Documentation</title>
    <phase>5: Enforcement &amp; Documentation</phase>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-hours>2</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>020, 035</dependencies>
    <blocks>043</blocks>
    <tags>documentation</tags>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Update docs/procedures/ci-cd-workflow.md and docs/procedures/testing-and-code-quality.md to reflect
    the complete quality pipeline implemented in this project. Document all new tools, workflows, and
    processes: the nightly quality workflow, CodeRabbit, Claude Code Action, SonarCloud, Prettier,
    Husky pre-commit hooks, and PSScriptAnalyzer. Include troubleshooting sections for the most common
    issues developers will encounter with each tool.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Technical writer and DevOps engineer with expertise in documenting CI/CD pipelines for development
    teams. Skilled at writing clear, maintainable procedure documents that serve both human developers
    and AI coding assistants.
  </role>

  <goal>
    Updated procedure documentation that accurately reflects the full quality system. Developers and
    AI agents can read these documents and understand: what quality checks run at each stage (pre-commit,
    PR, nightly, weekly), what each tool does, how to interpret results, and how to fix common issues.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      The existing procedure documents were written before this project and do not reflect the new
      tooling. They need to be updated (not replaced) with the new quality system components.

      New components to document in ci-cd-workflow.md:
      - Nightly quality workflow: trigger schedule, four jobs, issue creation, what to do when it fails
      - Claude Code Action: what it reviews, how to interpret PR comments, why it is advisory
      - CodeRabbit: what it reviews, how to configure per-PR review settings
      - Weekly summary: what it shows, how to read the trend table

      New components to document in testing-and-code-quality.md:
      - Prettier: configuration, how to run locally, what the CI check enforces
      - ESLint strictened rules: what rules were added, how to fix common violations, how to add
        justified suppressions (eslint-disable-next-line with comment)
      - Husky pre-commit hooks: what they check, how to skip in emergencies (git commit --no-verify
        with documented justification requirement), how to update them
      - PSScriptAnalyzer: what PowerShell files it checks, severity levels, how to fix findings
      - SonarCloud: how to access the dashboard, what the quality gate checks, how new-code coverage
        threshold works

      Each tool section should include:
      - What it does (one sentence)
      - When it runs (pre-commit / PR / nightly / weekly)
      - How to run it locally
      - How to interpret results
      - Troubleshooting: 2-3 most common issues and their fixes

      The documents should cross-reference each other where appropriate (e.g., ci-cd-workflow.md
      references testing-and-code-quality.md for tool details).
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>docs/procedures/ci-cd-workflow.md (modify — add nightly workflow, AI reviews, weekly summary)</file>
      <file>docs/procedures/testing-and-code-quality.md (modify — add Prettier, ESLint, Husky, PSScriptAnalyzer, SonarCloud sections)</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="spec">Existing procedure document content must be preserved. Updates are additive — add new sections, extend existing ones. Do not remove documentation for tools or processes that are still in use.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Documentation must be accurate to the actual implementation. Read the relevant workflow files and tool configurations before writing about them — do not describe idealized behavior that differs from what is actually deployed.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Each new tool section must include a "Run Locally" subsection so developers can reproduce CI checks on their machines before pushing.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Troubleshooting sections must be specific (e.g., "If Husky fails with 'permission denied', run chmod +x .husky/pre-commit") — not generic advice.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>docs/procedures/ci-cd-workflow.md</file>
      <file>docs/procedures/testing-and-code-quality.md</file>
      <file>.github/workflows/nightly-quality.yml</file>
      <file>.github/workflows/sdap-ci.yml</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Read docs/procedures/ci-cd-workflow.md in full to understand the current structure, existing sections, and tone. Identify where new content should be inserted without disrupting existing flow.</step>
    <step order="2">Read docs/procedures/testing-and-code-quality.md in full to map the existing structure and identify insertion points for the new tool sections.</step>
    <step order="3">Read .github/workflows/nightly-quality.yml and sdap-ci.yml to gather accurate details about trigger schedules, job names, and what each step does. Use this as the source of truth for documentation.</step>
    <step order="4">Update ci-cd-workflow.md: add a "Nightly Quality Workflow" section covering trigger (weeknight 6AM UTC), four jobs (tests, SonarCloud, AI review, dependency audit), issue creation, and how to interpret the nightly issue.</step>
    <step order="5">Update ci-cd-workflow.md: add a "Automated Code Review" section covering Claude Code Action (what it reviews, advisory status) and CodeRabbit (if deployed — check for .coderabbit.yaml or similar config). Add a "Weekly Quality Summary" section.</step>
    <step order="6">Update testing-and-code-quality.md: add sections for each new tool following the standard format (What it does / When it runs / Run locally / Interpret results / Troubleshooting). Tools to add: Prettier, ESLint (strictened rules), Husky, PSScriptAnalyzer, SonarCloud.</step>
    <step order="7">Add the "Run Locally" commands for each tool: `prettier --check "src/client/**/*.{ts,tsx}"`, `npx eslint src/client/ --max-warnings 0`, and the equivalent commands for running architecture tests and SonarCloud local scan.</step>
    <step order="8">Add troubleshooting subsections: common issues with Husky hooks (permission denied, hook not firing), common ESLint suppressions (when to use and how), common SonarCloud issues (coverage not updating, quality gate stuck).</step>
    <step order="9">Review both documents for cross-references: ensure ci-cd-workflow.md links to testing-and-code-quality.md for tool details, and vice versa for pipeline integration context.</step>
    <step order="10">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task 041 status from pending to completed.</step>
  </steps>

  <outputs>
    <output type="file">docs/procedures/ci-cd-workflow.md (updated with nightly workflow, AI reviews, weekly summary)</output>
    <output type="file">docs/procedures/testing-and-code-quality.md (updated with all new tool sections)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>ci-cd-workflow.md includes a Nightly Quality Workflow section with accurate schedule and job descriptions</criterion>
    <criterion>ci-cd-workflow.md includes sections for Claude Code Action and/or CodeRabbit AI reviews with advisory status clearly noted</criterion>
    <criterion>testing-and-code-quality.md includes sections for Prettier, ESLint strictened rules, Husky, PSScriptAnalyzer, and SonarCloud</criterion>
    <criterion>Each new tool section includes a "Run Locally" command</criterion>
    <criterion>Each new tool section includes at least 2 troubleshooting items</criterion>
    <criterion>All existing procedure document content is preserved</criterion>
    <criterion>Documentation is accurate to actual deployment (trigger times, job names match workflow files)</criterion>
    <criterion>TASK-INDEX.md updated to reflect task completion</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
